We now comment on the correlations among variables.

\(X_1\) is lightly positive correlated with both the human ecology variables, which means that the mean temperature of the cities does not effect their populations and that big enterprises are more present in colder cities but only slightly. It is positive correlated with the other climate variables but not with the inches of fallen rain, this might mean that in colder cities there are more rainy days but they do not bring much water, while in hotter cities the few rainy days bring a lot of water.

\(X_2\) has a very high correlation of \(.96\) with \(X_3\) stating that cities’ population grows together with the number of big enterprises. Both the variables have no strong correlation with the other ones except fot a light positive correlation with the wind speed, possibly because wind moves the smog so enterprises tend to grow in big cities because part of their smog production is ‘masked’ by the wind.

The last climate variables, \(X_4, \dots, X_6\) are lightly correlated among them, except for the ones related to precipitations that have a correlation of almost \(0.5\). This correlation is not high as one might expect and supports the speculation we made about hotter cities and intensity of the precipitations.

2.5

If we change the sign of \(\rho\) and set it to \(2/3\) the vector \(\mu\) does not change but the covariance matrix becomes

Sigz2
##           [,1]      [,2]
## [1,] 0.6666667 0.3333333
## [2,] 0.3333333 0.6666667

Since \(Z_1\) and \(Z_2\) are now positive correlated, we expect the ellipses to have the opposite orientation of the other one. In addition to this both the variances and the covariances are smaller in absolute value, so we expect the second ellipse to be smaller than the first one.

The ratio between the eigenvalues changes so the ratio between the squared semiaxes should change too.

eigen(Sigz)$values
## [1] 5.666667 1.000000
eigen(Sigz2)$values
## [1] 1.0000000 0.3333333

3.1

To choose how many components to retain in order to achieve a satisfactory low-dimensional representation of the data we consider we consider a few indicators:

  1. the number of variables that allows to explain at lease \(80/85 \%\) of the total variability;
  2. the numer of variables with corresponding variance greater than 1;
  3. an elbow on the screeplot.

We observe from the previous result that with 5 PC we explain the \(80\%\) of the total variability and with 6 the \(85\%\).

pendigits.Npca$sdev^2
##  [1] 4.71658637 3.22911210 2.57680630 1.22974181 1.06309928 0.79733935
##  [7] 0.60665163 0.54825156 0.41082409 0.29823086 0.21051266 0.11229691
## [13] 0.08048105 0.05800212 0.03426450 0.02779941

The first 5 variables have variances grater than 1, we use the screeplot to confirm 5 as the number of vaiables to be chosen.

screeplot(pendigits.Npca, type="lines", main="Screeplot for pendigits data")
abline(v=4, col="blue", lty=2, lwd=2)

The screeplot actually shows an evident elbow corresponding to the fourth variable. Since two indicators out of three suggest using 5 variables and by using four we explain less than \(75\%\) of the total variability, we choose to use 5 variables for the lower-dimensional representation of the dataset.

3.2

We consider only the first three principal components and investigate their multivariate normality by looking at the distribution of the Mahalanobis distances.

d <- as.data.frame(pendigits.Npca$x[,1:3])
Mala <- mahalanobis(d,center=colMeans(d),cov=round(var(d),4))
plot(density(Mala))
curve(dchisq(x, df = 3), from = 0, to = 15, add=TRUE,col = "red")

plot(qchisq(ppoints(Mala), df=3), sort(Mala), main= "Chisq Q-Q plot of Mahalanobis distance",
     xlab="Theoretical Quantiles",ylab="Sample Quantiles")
abline(0,1)

The qqplot does not support the normality of data because it stays below the line \(y=x\) and because of its tails. We can get to the same statement by looking at the distribution of the Mahalanobis distances and the true distribution of a Chi square with three degrees of freedom. The same consideration can be retrieved from the scatterplot of the principal components and from the plots of their univariate densities.

pairs(d)

plot(density(pendigits.Npca$x[,1]))

plot(density(pendigits.Npca$x[,2]))

plot(density(pendigits.Npca$x[,3]))

The densities show different maximums and look like mixtures of normal distributions. Since the dataset containts diffenent digits it could be interesting to repeat this analysis considering one digits at a time or groups of digits, isolating them and investigating their distribution with respect of the first three components. This could support or reject our consideration about the mixture of normal distributions.

3.3

We repeat the scatterplot and we color the points according to the digit they represent.

pairs(d,lower.panel=NULL,col=digit.col,pch=16)

The dataclouds show some underlying structure because they are visibly divided in clusters associated to different colors (and digits). This means that the first three principal components capture the sructure of the dataset which colud be impossible to visualize with sixteen features.
